04728nam a22007095i 9789048543915DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485439157 a10.1515/97890485439152doi  a(DE-B1597)583233  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aPN1993.C25 7aHIS0540002bisacsh04a791.4305091 aFairfax, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Red Years of Cahiers du cinéma (1968-1973) :bVolume II, Aesthetics and Ontology /cDaniel Fairfax. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (404 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm Culture in Transition00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tVolume II: Aesthetics and Ontology -- tPart III. Questions of Aesthetics -- tPart IV. Encounters with Ontology -- tConclusion -- tIndex of Names Cited0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe uprising which shook France in May 1968 also had a revolutionary effect on the country's most prominent film journal. Under editors Jean-Louis Comolli and Jean Narboni, Cahiers du cinéma embarked on a militant turn that would govern the journal's work over the next five years. With a Marxist orientation inspired by the thinking of Louis Althusser, Jacques Lacan and Roland Barthes, the "red years" of Cahiers du cinéma produced a theoretical outpouring that was formative for the establishment of film studies as an academic discipline in the 1970s, and is still of vital relevance for the contemporary audiovisual landscape. It was also the seminal experience for a generation of critics who have dedicated the following half-century to the task of critically responding to the cinema. The Red Years of Cahiers du Cinéma (1968-1973) gives a historical overview of this period in the journal's history, combining biographical accounts of the critics who were involved with Cahiers in the post-1968 and theoretical explorations of the text they wrote. Volume II centers on questions of aesthetics and the cinema's ontological relationship with the real.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMotion pictureszFrancexPeriodicals. 4aContemporary History. 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aPhilosophy. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aCahiers du cinéma, film theory, apparatus theory, political modernism, French cinema.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074322708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048543915?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048543915zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048543915/original  a978-3-11-074322-7 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-074335-7 DG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1 EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075408-7 EBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2021  